{"type":"message","id":"98a59b1b","parentId":"3a43fd9b","timestamp":"2026-03-24T14:27:43.740Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_g44u8gh11wxl_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"﻿# Pulse: 2026-03-24 102716\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state:\r\n\r\n1. Phase 0 COMPLETE - Sandbox foundation established\r\n2. Phase 1 COMPLETE - Architecture cross-analysis + integration spec synthesized\r\n3. Completed this session:\r\n   - Architecture cross-analysis\r\n   - Gap-decay synthesis\r\n   - LLM-augmented pulse working\r\n   - CFI Analysis with new findings\r\n\r\n4. Pending actions:\r\n   - CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\r\n   - Implement CFI filtering\r\n   - Distinguish constant format from research trajectory\r\n   - Wire to TemporalAttention backend\r\n   - Design actual compression network\r\n\r\nThe most actionable item seems to be the CFI-weighted compression experiment. Looking at the CFI_RESULTS.md, they found:\r\n- 44.8% have CFI=0 (pure noise/metaprogramming)\r\n- Only 5.7% have CFI>=0.7 (true causal anchors)\r\n- Mean CFI is 0.181\r\n\r\nThe next step is to implement a CFI-weighted compression experiment to compare against the frequency baseline. This would involve:\r\n1. Computing CFI for each invariant\r\n2. Using CFI weights instead of frequency weights\r\n3. Testing prediction quality\r\n\r\nLet me check what's in the research directory to understand the current state of files.\r\n\r\nI need to create an experiment design for CFI-weighted compression. The key insight is that we should filter out the CFI=0 invariants (noise) and weight the CFI>0.7 invariants higher than the frequency-based approach.\r\n\r\nLet me create a concrete action - I'll create a CFI-weighted compression experiment specification that can be executed.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nCFI analysis revealed that 44.8% of invariants are pure noise (CFI=0) while only 5.7% are true causal anchors (CFI≥0.7). This suggests a CFI-weighted compression should outperform frequency-based compression by filtering noise and prioritizing causal signals.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate CFI-weighted compression experiment specification and initial implementation in research directory. This will test whether CFI-weighting improves next-pulse prediction compared to frequency baseline.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression will outperform frequency-weighted compression for next-pulse prediction because:\r\n1. Filters out metaprogramming noise (CFI=0)\r\n2. Prioritizes true causal anchors (CFI≥0.7)\r\n3. Reduces false pattern recognition from frequency artifacts\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Baseline: Frequency-Weighted Compression\r\n```\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 10:27:35\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774362463738}}
